## The Memory Leak: Root Cause Analysis

This component has **two compounding bugs** that together cause unbounded accumulation of event listeners. Every time the user navigates back to the page, more listeners pile onto `window` and are never removed.

### Issue 1: No cleanup function returned from `useEffect`

The effect calls `window.addEventListener(...)` but never returns a cleanup function. When the component unmounts (navigating away), the listeners stay attached to the global `window` object. Since `window` outlives the component, the handler closures — and everything they capture — can never be garbage collected.

### Issue 2: Missing dependency array

`useEffect(() => {...})` with **no second argument** runs *after every render*. Every state update (`setScrollY`, `setScrollDirection`, `setLastScrollY`) triggers a re-render, which re-runs the effect, which adds *yet another* pair of listeners. So even within a single mount, listeners multiply on every scroll tick.

### Issue 3: Anonymous handlers can't be removed

`removeEventListener` works by *reference identity*. It only removes a listener if you pass the exact same function object that was registered. Because the original code uses inline arrow functions:

```js
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });  // anonymous — no reference kept
```

…there is no stored reference to pass to `removeEventListener` later. Even if you *added* a cleanup function, you couldn't remove these specific anonymous closures — each `() => {}` is a brand-new, unique object. You must name the handlers (or hold them in a variable) so the same reference is available to both add and remove.

### The lifecycle, step by step

```
Mount        → effect runs → adds listener #1, #2
scroll fires → setState    → re-render → effect runs AGAIN → adds #3, #4 ...
...                                                            (grows forever)
Unmount      → no cleanup  → all listeners remain on window, leaked
Re-navigate  → mount again → starts over, ON TOP of the orphaned ones
```

After a few navigation cycles you have hundreds of live scroll/resize handlers, each firing on every scroll event — hence the lag.

### React 18 Strict Mode makes it obvious in dev

In development, React 18 Strict Mode **intentionally mounts, unmounts, then remounts** every component once, double-invoking effects. This is a deliberate probe: if your effect is written correctly, the cleanup from the first invocation removes the first listener before the second invocation adds it again — net zero leak. If cleanup is missing (as here), you immediately see **two** sets of listeners after a single mount, surfacing the bug during development instead of in production. A correctly written effect passes the Strict Mode double-invoke test cleanly.

---

## Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY] = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');

    // Track last scroll position in a ref instead of state.
    // This avoids re-renders (and effect re-runs) just to remember the
    // previous value, and prevents a stale-closure bug on lastScrollY.
    const lastScrollY = useRef(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // Named handler references so the SAME function objects can be
        // passed to both addEventListener and removeEventListener.
        const handleScroll = () => {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;
            setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollY.current ? 'down' : 'up');
            lastScrollY.current = currentScrollY;
            setScrollY(currentScrollY);
        };

        const handleResize = () => {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        };

        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // Cleanup: runs on unmount AND before any re-run of the effect.
        // Removes exactly the listeners we added (matching references).
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
        };
    }, []); // Empty dependency array: attach listeners ONCE on mount.

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

### What changed and why

| Fix | Effect |
|-----|--------|
| **Empty dependency array `[]`** | Effect runs once on mount, not after every render — no per-scroll listener accumulation. |
| **`return () => {...}` cleanup** | Listeners are removed on unmount, so navigating away leaves nothing behind. |
| **Named `handleScroll` / `handleResize`** | Same reference is available to `removeEventListener`, so cleanup actually works. |
| **`lastScrollY` as a `useRef`** | Avoids a subtle second bug: with `[]` deps, a `lastScrollY` *state* value would be captured stale inside the handler closure (frozen at 0 forever, breaking direction detection). A ref always reads the current value (`.current`) without causing re-renders or effect re-runs. |

### Why the ref matters (a trap in the naive fix)

If you only add cleanup + `[]` but keep `lastScrollY` as state, the handler closure captures `lastScrollY`'s value from the *first* render (`0`) and never sees updates — because the effect never re-runs to recreate the closure. Direction would always be computed against `0`. Using a ref sidesteps this entirely: `lastScrollY.current` always reflects the latest value, and updating it never triggers a render.

### Functional equivalence

The corrected version preserves all original behavior — it tracks `scrollY`, computes `'up'`/`'down'` direction by comparing against the previous position, logs on resize, and renders the same fixed overlay. It simply does so without leaking listeners and with correct direction detection.

